1. SETUP AN EMPTY REPO IN GITHUB CALLED SIMPLE GB BATTERY,

2. STARTED AMP WITH THIS THREAD -> GET DATA WRAPPERS FOR SOLAR, WIND AND DEMAND FORECASTS
This is a project in which I intend to build a basic battery with input parameters for the GB energy system.
For this I will need to pull the data from BMRS. I need to pull the demand, wind, and solar generation data and the day ahead cleared prices.
The base url for the bmrs website is bmrs.elexon.co.uk.
Can you please write the code that pulls the wind, solar, and demand
outturn data for a given date and wrap it up with a for loop that loops from the 90 days ago until today?
Create a file called bmrs_data_wrapper.py and dump all this code in there.

3. AMENDED THE CODE PRODUCED BY AMP TO CORRECT THE TOTAL WIND FORECAST (BY SUMMING UP THE WIND ONSHORE AND WIND OFFSHORE)

4. AMP QUERY - ADD THE MARKET INDEX PRICE TO THE FUNDAMENTALS.
In the bmrs_data_wrapper.py there is a function called bmrs_data_wrapper_main_function which is the main trigger point for the data pulling from bmrs.
Inside this function there is a fetch day data function pulls the demand, wind and solar and it merges them together.
Here i want to pull another dataset from bmrs which is the market index prices. The link for this bmrs.elexon.co.uk/market-index-prices.
I want you to write the code that pull sthe market index prices and merges it to the df that is merged with wind solar and demand mws.

5. AMP QUERY - ADD THE FUNDAMENTAL FORECASTS TO THE BMRS DATA WRAPPER
So far we have collected the actuals for fundamentals. We want to pull the day ahead wind, solar, and demand forecasts from bmrs.
in bmrs_data_wrapper.py create a new function called get_bmrs_day_ahead_forecasts and pull the solar, wind, and demand forecasts.

6. AMP QUERY - CHARACTERISE THE HISTORIC ACTUAL DAY-AHEAD PRICES WITH HISTORIC OUTTURN RESIDUAL LOAD, and PLOT IT

7. CALCULATED THE CURVEFITTED PRICE FROM THE FORECASTED RESIDUAL LOAD.

8. AMP QUERY - WRITING A BATTERY OPTIMISER
Okay so i want you to use pulp for the optimisation. the battery_module.py will have a function called optimise battery.
it will take the curvefitted_price as input (48 values for every settlement period).
the battery will be able to charge or discharge at 1 MW for every settlement period. i want the battery to have state of energy of 2 mwh.
this means that it can charge for 4 settlement periods or discharge for 4 settlement periods. every settlement period is 30 minutes.

9. AMP QUERY - ADDING A NEW CONSTRAINT FOR LIMITTING CYCLES

okay now i want POWER_MW, CAPACITY_MWH to be inputs to the optimise battery module. I also want to apply an additional constraint which is the
cumulative sum of charge to be less than equal to input cycle multiplied with POWER_MW and cummulative sum of discharge to be less than or equal
 to the input cycle multipled with POWER_MW. So if I have inputted 2 for a 1 MW battery, this means that i can have 4 charge values (in 48 settlement
 periods where each one is 30 minutes) with 1 MW values, and I can have 4 discharge values with similar logic.
